Introduction¶

This project analyzes the dataset named "Medical Appointment No Shows". This dataset collects information from over 100k medical appointments in Brazil and is focused on the question of whether or not patients show up to their appointments. A number of characteristics about the patient are included in each row. The source of this data can be found at: Kaggle.

One person schedules an appointment, but still does not show up. Can we understand why this happens? Here, I will investigate a series of questions on this dataset (see below) with a variety of descriptive statistics and graphical representations. For this, first I will load, inspect and modify the dataset in order to clean it and prepare it for further analysis. Then, I will briefly describe the nature of the variables. Further, I will calculate various descriptive measures and graphical representations to look at the differences between groups of interest. Each question will be handled separately. I will end my analysis with a final section summing up my conclusions of this analysis.

Questions¶

  1. Do no-shows occur more often in specific days or months?
  2. Do no-shows occur more often among men or women?
  3. Are no-shows related with a person's health status?
  4. Is social support influencing the rate of appointment no-shows?
  5. Is distance from appointment locations related to no-shows?
  6. Does the SMS message number influence the rate of no-shows?

Short description:¶

The dataset is composed of 14 variables (columns) and 110527 observations (rows), with no missing values. Variables may be of different types and nature. Unique identification numbers (IDs) are numerical variables, personal information (age, gender, address and health condition) are numerical or categorical, as well as appointment information (schedule time and SMS reminders). The dependent variable of interest is 'No-show' which means whether the patient did or did not go to the appointment.

  • "PatientId" and "AppointmentID" are set as numerical (i.e., float and int), but probably they should be analyzed as categorical variables (strings).
  • Variables related to date ("ScheduleDay" and "AppointmentDay") are set as strings, but they should be set to datetime, in order for analysis to account for the specific time-points, not only weekdays, but maybe also months and years.
  • "Scholarship" is of integer type ("0/1", which actually represents "no/yes"). The same is true for "Hipertension", "Diabetes", "Alcoholism", "Handcap" and "SMS_received".
  • For age, we may notice a negative value in its range. Since age cannot be negative, this must be corrected.

What needs to be done:¶

Not all variables, however, would be interesting to use in the analysis. For example "AppointmentID" might not be informative to relate to "No-show", or the time an appointment was set, i.e., "ScheduleDay". These variables could be removed from the dataset, to spare some computing time and memory usage during the analysis. In addition, variable names could be edited, for better comprehension and ease of coding. Moreover, "No-show" may be a tricky variable, and perhaps the opposite may be more easy for understanding the analysis. That is, whether persons did indeed go to the appointments ("attendance"). Finally, there might be duplicated rows in the data, thus it needs to be further checked. In summary, we need to:

  • Check for duplicates or NAs and remove them
  • Remove unimportant variables
  • Rename variable names
  • Modify variable class types
  • Create new values for dates and for successful appointments
  • Check age values that are negative

Numerical variables:¶

Note: Appointment year was omited here, because appointments were only taken in one year (2016).

Observations
Taking a look at the numerical variable histograms and pair-wise plots, we may come up with some remarks.

Distribution:
(1) Observing the age of patients, we notice that there is a steep increase in age close to 0 and a slower decrease towards the age of 100. No particular age is overrepresented, except for the age close to 0, suggesting that many patients were very young. (2) More than half of the patients did not receive notifications by SMS. (3) Apointments were mostly in May, then June and less frequently in average in April. (4) Appointments were set mostly in the middle of the week (Wednesday) and less frequently towards weekends.

Relationship:
No strong relationships can be seen between any pair-wise variable combination in this dataset for the numerical variables. The graphs above (scater plots) show the distribution of points (observations) with no particular trend, such as a line that could suggest correlations.

Patients with scholarships are found only in about 1/8 of the appointments. Regarding health conditions, we also notice that most of the appointments were set for patients without hipertension, diabetes, alcoholism or with a handcap condition. From those, patients with hipertension were the most frequent, constituting almost 1/4 of the appointments.

The graph above shows a scatter plot with a regression line and 95% confidence interval. Looks like the more SMS messages a patient have, the more she/he goes to appointments. I.e., no-shows are lower for patients with more SMS reminders. Patients that are more often reminded about an appointment indeed go to the doctor!

Conclusions¶

This analysis covered a few aspects of the dataset "Medical Appointment No Shows". Data suggests that patient attendance to consultations in Brazil might be related to some socio-demographic aspects of patients. Below are the main conclusions regarding the specific Questions posed at the beginning of this document.

Answering the questions:¶

  1. date: we cannot observe a strong pattern of month or weekday on appointment attendance. Suggesting that attendance to appointments is not related to specific months or days of the week.

  2. gender: men and women had similar attendance rates (80.27% and 80.4%, respectively).

  3. health conditions: namely hipertension, diabetes, alcoholism and handcap, do not seem to influence the rate of attendances (and consequently no-shows), but it must be taken into account that patients with health condition were very scarce and therefore conclusions might not be strong.

  4. social support (if patients had scholarships): there seems to be a slight negative trend related to attendance. I.e., patients with scholarships came relatively fewer times to appointments compared to patients without scholarships. This difference was about 5.2% (rate of patients with scholarship was 0.77 against 0.81 on the other group). This difference is not so striking.

  5. neighbourhood: usually it did not matter much to the attendance rate. Some particular neighbourhoods, however, did indeed have strong differences in attendance rate. This, suggests that distance from residence to appointment location might influence the number of no-shows in doctoral appointments.

  6. SMS messages: we found that the more messages a patient received, the more the patient seemed to come to appointments.

Limitations of this analysis:¶

It is still important to bare in mind that these analysis are descriptive and no statistical tests have been carried out. In other words, we cannot truly explain the behavior of patients regarding their attendance to medical consultations by only looking at these few variables represented in some graphical visualizations. Statistical tests should also be performed, perhaps including additional variables that were not covered here in order for us to make stronger interpretations about this dataset.
